The central design choice of the library is that all geometry reduces to a set of points. A point carries its location in the working coordinate system (x, y), its geographic location (lon, lat), and — where meaningful — a representative area and cell spacing (dx, dy). Every operation (distance, projection, neighbor search, interpolation) is defined on points.
A grid is then nothing more than points laid out on a structured 2D mesh, plus axis metadata describing that mesh. This is why the library can interpolate equally well between two grids, between scattered observations and a grid, or between polygons and a grid — they are all just points underneath.





classDiagram
    class points_class {
      +npts
      +x(:) y(:) lon(:) lat(:)
      +area(:) dx(:) dy(:)
      +mtype, units, planet, proj
    }
    class grid_class {
      +npts
      +x(:,:) y(:,:) lon(:,:) lat(:,:)
      +area(:,:)
      +G : grid_axis_class
    }
    class grid_axis_class {
      +nx ny
      +x0 dx y0 dy
      +x(:) y(:)
    }
    class map_class {
      +npts nmax
      +map(:) : pt_wts_class
    }
    class pt_wts_class {
      +n
      +i(:) dist(:) weight(:) area(:)
      +quadrant(:) border(:)
    }
    grid_class --&gt; grid_axis_class
    grid_class ..&gt; points_class : grid_to_points
    points_class ..&gt; grid_class : points_to_grid
    map_class --&gt; pt_wts_class

